	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB2719_01.jpg"/> The persons in question have given us the following information: Before they entrained us
				and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deported</term> us to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Auschwitz-Birkenau</placeName> we stayed for around five
				weeks in the brick factory of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Munkács</placeName>. At the station they
				separated us from our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">parents</term>, whom we never
				saw again. We went into <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">Camp A</term>, from where we
				were led to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">Brezinka</term> 5 days later. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> here till December. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">Brezinka</term> was constructed in the middle,
				surrounded by 5 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematoria</term>. We received and
				sorted out all the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836">clothes</term> and the luggage
				that <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deported</term> people had brought. We also
				found our own stuff, and we wanted to put on our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject"
					>sweaters</term> because we were very <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>cold</term>. However, when they noticed it they gave us 25 blows and seized all that we had. The only thing we could save was a
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-701">photo</term> of our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">father</term> that we found also in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">Brezinka</term> among the several thousands of other
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-701">photos</term>. We hid it in our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">shoes</term> and that was how we kept it for a year,
				which was quite a thing because they searched us all the time and more than once they took our old <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> and gave us new ones. We still have the
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-701">photo</term> even if it is torn and tattered. It
				is the only memory that remained of our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
					>parents</term>. <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB2719_02.jpg"/> Day by day we saw the long queues that led to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematoria</term> but we never saw anyone returning
				from there. Around half of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> who had
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> for three months in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-555" type="camp">Krakow</placeName> and came back here were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">singled out</term> although those were young and fit
				for work. Once every four weeks we had a day off, when we had to go to a concert. Jewish boys and girls had to play instruments, sing
				and dance while a few metres away endless queues of innocent people headed towards their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-529" type="subject">horrible end</term>. Yet, a boy could not speak with a
				girl because they would immediately send you to a punishment <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-489"
					type="subject">kommando</term> to shovel coal or do some other kind of difficult job. In December, when no new <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transports</term> arrived and when they made disappear
				all traces of this horrible <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-529" type="subject">extermination</term> of
				people, and burnt also the men whom they had forced to assist with burning, we were also transferred from this place to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2849156/reichenbach-vogtland.html">Reichenbach</placeName>. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> for the radio factory Telefunken.
					The<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> supervised us but we had a
				relatively good <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">life</term>. We got 300 grams of
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> and twice a day cooked warm <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">food</term>. We stayed here till the middle of
				February, when they made us depart on foot, and we did around 150 kilometres. For the whole time we got a kilo of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> each. The journey lasted for four days,
				and we spent the nights in school buildings. There were 1,000 of us, and we were always lodged in such a small place that we could
				hardly sit down, so every morning we stood up more tired and worn. We arrived in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3063907/trutnov.html">Trautenau</placeName>, and spent there three days. We did not get any <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> only some warm water with a few <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">potato</term> peels. They put us here in open <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">wagons</term> and we travelled for 7 days. Meanwhile,
				the rail system was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105" type="subject">bombed</term> at several points
				and we travelled back and forth; they did know where to go. It was a horrible journey. We arrived in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp">Bergen- Belsen</placeName> and thought our journey had
				finally ended and we could have a rest at least for a night even if on the floor. But they did not receive us either here. The <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522">train</term> stood still 24 hours before we departed
				again. We arrived in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2908947/hausberge-an-der-porta.html">Porta</placeName> and remained
				there. This was a new<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>. We got 100 grams
				of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> and some watery <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">soup</term> a day but had to work 12 hours without a
				break. We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> in an underground <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>. We had to cross a high hill to get to
				the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>. Our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">wooden clogs</term> were torn to pieces and we
				remained barefoot. Our weak bodies could not cope with the steep slope. Girls fainted one after the other, girls who had earlier got
				on so well despite the scarcity. We got down into the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>, which was not fully finished yet. Everything was
				perfectly new and shiny; but it was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">dark and
					airless</term>. The lack of sunshine and fresh air was horrible. Again and again we felt as though we would not get any fresh air
				and drown. <pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB2719_03.jpg"/> 5 weeks later, we left for <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-703" type="camp">Fallersleben</placeName>. The journey lasted for 2 days.
				We got not even a bite of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">food</term> or a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">drop of water</term> during these two days, and were
				not allowed to go to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">toilet</term>. On the first
				day we arrived, we still did not get anything to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>eat</term>, and we believed we were to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-570" type="subject"
					>starve</term> to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term>. The following
				day, finally we got some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">soup</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term>. We stayed here for 5 days before they
				newly entrained us and the next day we arrived in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-746" type="camp"
					>Salzwedel</placeName>. The first day we got nothing to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">eat</term>, the second day 50 grams of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">bread</term> and a plate of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>soup</term>. There were already a lot of people kept here when we arrived and there were no places for us, not even a little
				straw, so we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">slept</term> on bare floor. In the last
				days we did not get <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> either here and we
				could not see any <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">water</term>. We got only the
				usual dried <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">potatoes</term>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">squalor</term> that was in the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567">camp</term> is unimaginable. <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> wanted to set fire to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> together with us but the ca. 150 <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_french">French</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-511" type="subject">prisoners of war</term>, who stayed here, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-214" type="subject">saved our lives</term> with composure and courage. Our
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">parents</term>, two younger <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brothers</term>, our elder <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term> and elder <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">sister</term> with her two little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> all <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName>. All that we desire is <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">to get to Palestine</term>.</p>
